2026-05-09 | Cyclically Rotate Matrix Layers

Question
Return matrix after all rotations.
	Key Insight
Instead of rotating one step k times:
		extract each layer into an array  
Then:
		perform cyclic rotation using modulo  
Finally:
		put rotated values back into matrix.
	Approach
1.	Process each layer independently  
2.	Extract layer elements in traversal order:
		top row  
		right column  
		bottom row  
		left column  
3.	Rotate array left by:
		k % layerSize  
4.	Write rotated values back into matrix
		using same traversal order  
	Time Complexity
	O(m × n)
	Space Complexity
	O(m × n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> rotateGrid(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {
        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();
        int layers = min(m, n) / 2;
        for(int layer = 0; layer < layers; layer++){
            vector<int> elems;
            int top = layer;
            int left = layer;
            int bottom = m - layer - 1;
            int right = n - layer - 1;
            // top row
            for(int j = left; j <= right; j++)
                elems.push_back(grid[top][j]);
            // right col
            for(int i = top + 1; i <= bottom - 1; i++)
                elems.push_back(grid[i][right]);
            // bottom row
            for(int j = right; j >= left; j--)
                elems.push_back(grid[bottom][j]);
            // left col
            for(int i = bottom - 1; i >= top + 1; i--)
                elems.push_back(grid[i][left]);
            int sz = elems.size();
            int rot = k % sz;
            vector<int> rotated(sz);
            for(int i = 0; i < sz; i++){
                rotated[i] = elems[(i + rot) % sz];
            }
            int idx = 0;
            // top row
            for(int j = left; j <= right; j++)
                grid[top][j] = rotated[idx++];
            // right col
            for(int i = top + 1; i <= bottom - 1; i++)
                grid[i][right] = rotated[idx++];
            // bottom row
            for(int j = right; j >= left; j--)
                grid[bottom][j] = rotated[idx++];
            // left col
            for(int i = bottom - 1; i >= top + 1; i--)
                grid[i][left] = rotated[idx++];
        }
        return grid;
    }
};
	Key Insight
The main trick:
		treat every layer as a circular array  
Then rotation becomes:
		simple cyclic shift problem  
This avoids expensive repeated simulation.
